Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and chopped into 1/2cm pieces). Drain and rinse the @sweetcorn{1} and @black beans{1} in a #colander{}. Cut each @dried apricots{40}(cut into quarters) into quarters. Heat a glug of oil in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat and add half the onion. Cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Then add half the @chicken stock pot{1}, @water for the stock{100%ml} and @coconut milk{200%ml}. Bring to the boil, stir to dissolve and then add the @basmati rice{150%g}.

Add two-thirds of both the sweetcorn and black beans to the rice. Mix and bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium-low, cover with a #lid{} and simmer, ~{10%minutes}. Remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes}.

> TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

While the rice cooks, heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the @British beef mince{250%g}. Cook until browned, breaking it up with a #spoon{}, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add the remaining onion to the beef and cook until softened, stirring occasionally, another ~{5%minutes}. Add the apricots, @poudre de colombo{1.5} and @tomato puree{30%g}. Stir together and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @mango chutney{40%g}, remaining stock pot and @water for the beef{100%ml} to the frying pan. Bring to a simmer and gently bubble until the sauce is rich and thick, ~{5-7%minutes}.

As the beef is cooking, roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all) and pop it in a #small bowl{}. Mix in the remaining sweetcorn and black beans. Zest the @lime{1/2}(zested) and set aside. Cut the lime in half and squeeze a little of the juice into the sweetcorn and beans. Stir in the @olive oil{1}, add a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @pepper{grind}. Mix well... that's the salsa done!

When the rice is cooked, fluff it up with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest. Serve it in #bowls{} with the Caribbean beef on top and some sweetcorn salsa. Enjoy!